You need to account for ranges that cover midnight, e.g.

```
if (endHour &lt; startHour) {
  endHour += 24;
}
if (currentHour &lt; startHour) {
  currentHour += 24;
}

// now check if currentHour between start and end
```

Do note however that [`LocalDateTime#getHour()`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/LocalDateTime.html#getHour--) returns a value between 0 and 23 already. So 9 means 9AM and 21 means 9PM.

The value `9` does not mean the same thing as `9pm` or `21`; it means `9am` or simply `9`.

You need to use `21`.

```java
import java.time.LocalDateTime;
import java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit;

public class TimeRangeChecker {
    private static final int HOURS_PER_DAY = (int) TimeUnit.DAYS.toHours(1); // 24

    public static boolean isInBetween(LocalDateTime localDateTime, int startHour, int endHour) {
        int computedEndHour = endHour &lt; startHour ? endHour + HOURS_PER_DAY: endHour;
        int currHour = localDateTime.getHour();
        return currHour &gt;= startHour &amp;&amp; currHour &lt; computedEndHour;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        LocalDateTime now = LocalDateTime.now().withHour(21); // 9pm
        System.out.println(isInBetween(now, 20, 1)); // false
    }
}
```

